https://prez.dev/description.@value: This vocabulary lists the fundamental types of geological features that are used to define the geological framework/4D evolution of Western Australia and are relevant to the duties of the Geological Survey of Western Australia. A geological feature is a physical or conceptual feature that is hypothesized to exist coherently in the Earth and that results from geological processes (definition largely derived from SWEET ontology http://sweetontology.net/realmGeol#geologicfeature).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A body of unconsolidated to secondarily recemented materials that overlies more coherent bedrock, and that has been formed and shaped by weathering, erosion, transport and/or deposition of older material. It includes the weathered component of the underlying bedrock.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#hist.@value: One of the foundation elements in GSWA's Explanatory Notes System, used to define the geological framework of an area. Definition adapted from Eggleton, RA (ed.) 2001, The regolith glossary: surficial geology, soils and landscapes: Cooperative Research Centre for Landscape Evolution and Mineral Exploration (CRC LEME), Canberra, Australian Capital Territory, 144p.
